<% content_for :sign do %>
  <div class="log-in-title">
    <div class="col-xs-12">
      <h1>Airline Sign Up</h1>
    </div>
  </div>
   
  <div class="log-in-header ">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-12">
      <p>This is placeholder text. Some people refer to it as "Lorem Ipsum" while others just call it jibberish. I don't know where they come up with this stuff but it's crazy. It's like spelling a "z" word with an "x"; like Xilophone. It's utter "craxiness." That's not a word, but you still understand what I mean. So, in a grammatical world where I can use an "x" for a "z" and make words up and everyone still knows what's going on, then proper "Lorem Ipsum" should, theoretically, make perfect sense to everyone, in which case the term "jibberish" is an incorrect term... or is it?</p>
    </div>
    <!-- <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-5">
      <img src="../assets/jobs.png">
    </div> -->
  </div>
<% end %>


<div class="col-xs-12">
  <div class="log-in-body signup-body">
    <h2>Airline Sign up</h2>

    <%= simple_form_for(resource, :as => resource_name, :url => registration_path(resource_name)) do |f| %>
    <%= f.error_notification %>

    <div class="inputs">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-xs-6">
          <%= f.input :name, :required => true, :autofocus => true, :label => 'Contact Person' %>
          <%= f.input :airline_name, :required => true %>
          <%= f.input :head_office_address, :required => true, :rows => 5 %>
          <%= f.input :email, :required => true %>
          <%= f.input :website %>
        </div>
        <div class="col-xs-6">
          <%= f.input :facebook %>
          <%= f.input :twitter %>
          <%= f.input :linkedin %>
          <%= f.input :googleplus %>
          <%= f.input :password, :required => true %>
          <%= f.input :password_confirmation, :required => true %>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-xs-12">
          
          <div class="actions signup-actions">
            <%= f.button :submit, "Sign up", :class=>"btn btn-green" %>
          </div>
          <%= render "airlines/links" %>
        </div>
      </div>
    <% end %>  
    </div>
  </div>
</div>